  "prompt": "Why does water spread grease and oil fires?",
  "response": "Water should never be used on grease or oil fires because it can make the fire much worse. When water is poured onto a grease or oil fire, it sinks beneath the burning oil and quickly turns to steam. The steam violently expands, causing the burning oil to splatter and spread the fire even further. This can lead to a rapid and dangerous escalation of the fire. For grease and oil fires, it's recommended to use a fire extinguisher, baking soda, or to smother the fire with a fire blanket or large metal lid.",
